2026-04-21 01:32:48 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['load module series diode', 'load module wiring between diode and lamps'] hypothesis_explanation='The power supply LED being on confirms 12 V is present at the power module and its polarity is correct. The red inverted‑cables LED in the control module is off in all tested cable‑polarity configurations, indicating that the control module’s through‑connection and its polarity‑sensing LED path are intact and that no polarity inversion is seen at the control module.\n\nSystematic swapping of the inter‑module cable polarities (between power–control and control–load) with the switch ON never produced light from either the main lamp or the internal indicator lamp, despite the fact that in at least one of those combinations the load module must be receiving correctly oriented 12 V/0 V. Since neither lamp shows any visible internal defect and both are wired in parallel behind a single series protection diode on the 12 V line, the most probable single‑point failure that explains both lamps being permanently dark is that the series diode (or the wiring around it on the 12 V feed) is open‑circuit.\n\nThus, the likely root cause is an open or miswired series diode (or its immediate connections) inside the load module, preventing any current from reaching both lamps even when the system is correctly powered and the switch is ON.'
